WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.000 --> 00:00:02.667
RONALD SMITH: Well,
I'm talking about storms, but

00:00:02.667 --> 00:00:06.300
someone asked me a question the
other day about why the

00:00:06.300 --> 00:00:08.933
Coriolis force is opposite
in the two hemispheres.

00:00:08.933 --> 00:00:12.233
And I can't give you a complete
explanation, but I

00:00:12.233 --> 00:00:16.767
can give you a partial
explanation.

00:00:16.767 --> 00:00:19.933
Here's the globe, and of course,
it spins toward the

00:00:19.933 --> 00:00:23.667
east. The sun rises in the east,
sets in the west. So

00:00:23.667 --> 00:00:26.067
that's the way the
Earth spins.

00:00:26.067 --> 00:00:29.500
If I keep spinning it in that
direction and I face this

00:00:29.500 --> 00:00:32.733
towards you, is that clockwise
or counterclockwise?

00:00:35.300 --> 00:00:36.600
Counterclockwise.

00:00:36.600 --> 00:00:40.600
I'm going to keep spinning
it in that direction.

00:00:40.600 --> 00:00:43.800
Is that clockwise or
counterclockwise?

00:00:43.800 --> 00:00:45.067
Clockwise.

00:00:45.067 --> 00:00:52.600
So in a sense, while the globe
spins eastward, the sense of

00:00:52.600 --> 00:00:57.033
rotation is opposite in
the two hemispheres.

00:00:57.033 --> 00:01:00.600
And that is one way to
understand why the Coriolis

00:01:00.600 --> 00:01:03.967
force is opposite in the
two hemispheres.

00:01:03.967 --> 00:01:07.333
So like I said, not a complete
explanation, but it's true,

00:01:07.333 --> 00:01:12.367
and I think it helps to
understand that tricky point

00:01:12.367 --> 00:01:15.167
about the Coriolis force.

00:01:15.167 --> 00:01:16.433
Any questions on that?

00:01:20.133 --> 00:01:23.633
So we're going through
storms today.

00:01:23.633 --> 00:01:27.167
This is not very quantitative
material.

00:01:27.167 --> 00:01:29.967
This stuff will be posted
after the fact, and your

00:01:29.967 --> 00:01:31.167
textbook is very good.

00:01:31.167 --> 00:01:33.800
These chapters that I've
assigned, a number of them

00:01:33.800 --> 00:01:38.300
have to do with storm
types and so on.

00:01:38.300 --> 00:01:39.467
So you'll find a good-- of
course, I will explain things

00:01:39.467 --> 00:01:42.600
somewhat differently, but you'll
find a good way to get

00:01:42.600 --> 00:01:45.967
competing views of this by
listening to what I say and

00:01:45.967 --> 00:01:48.867
then reading the textbook, and
between the two, you should

00:01:48.867 --> 00:01:53.000
come out pretty well
on this subject.

00:01:53.000 --> 00:02:04.167
So we were talking about
convective storms. And that is

00:02:04.167 --> 00:02:08.367
the class of storms that get
their energy from the release

00:02:08.367 --> 00:02:09.833
of latent heat.

00:02:09.833 --> 00:02:11.733
I mentioned this last time.

00:02:11.733 --> 00:02:13.600
That's a number that I carry
around in my head.

00:02:13.600 --> 00:02:17.167
It's rounded off a little bit,
but I use that number so often

00:02:17.167 --> 00:02:18.433
that I carry it around
in my head.

00:02:18.433 --> 00:02:21.667
The latent heat of condensation,
or if you like,

00:02:21.667 --> 00:02:23.533
the latent heat of
evaporation--

00:02:23.533 --> 00:02:27.400
it's the same magnitude,
independent of whether you're

00:02:27.400 --> 00:02:30.800
condensing or evaporating
water-- is about 2 and 1/2

00:02:30.800 --> 00:02:33.600
million joules per kilogram.

00:02:33.600 --> 00:02:37.833
And so when you condense water,
you're then providing

00:02:37.833 --> 00:02:42.367
extra heat to the air, which
makes it warmer, more buoyant.

00:02:42.367 --> 00:02:48.033
It's likely to rise then, and
that's what's going on in all

00:02:48.033 --> 00:02:50.400
of these storms. It's the basic

00:02:50.400 --> 00:02:52.167
underlying energy source.

00:02:52.167 --> 00:02:54.300
We talked about air-mass
thunderstorms last time and

00:02:54.300 --> 00:02:57.500
how they go through
a life cycle.

00:02:57.500 --> 00:02:59.000
And after--

00:02:59.000 --> 00:03:03.967
they take about 20 minutes to
30 minutes to develop from a

00:03:03.967 --> 00:03:08.033
fair-weather cumulus into a
cumulonimbus with rain coming

00:03:08.033 --> 00:03:09.400
out the bottom.

00:03:09.400 --> 00:03:13.333
And then as the rain begins,
you begin to get some

00:03:13.333 --> 00:03:16.400
evaporation of falling
rainwater

00:03:16.400 --> 00:03:18.533
just below cloud base.

00:03:18.533 --> 00:03:23.333
That produces cool air, which
then sinks and spreads out.

00:03:23.333 --> 00:03:27.533
It's like you open your freezer
door, and that cold

00:03:27.533 --> 00:03:30.567
air from the freezer falls down
to the kitchen floor and

00:03:30.567 --> 00:03:32.333
then spreads out.

00:03:32.333 --> 00:03:35.800
That's what's happening, and
that goes by various names.

00:03:35.800 --> 00:03:39.933
Sometimes we call it a
downburst. Sometimes it's

00:03:39.933 --> 00:03:42.000
called a gust front.

00:03:42.000 --> 00:03:43.500
The front of it is called
the gust front.

00:03:43.500 --> 00:03:46.567
But anyway, the air is now
spreading out away from the

00:03:46.567 --> 00:03:51.433
cloud, and that shuts off
the warm, moist inflow.

00:03:51.433 --> 00:03:54.700
So it kills itself
off, basically.

00:03:54.700 --> 00:03:56.000
It has a-- after about
two hours, it's gone.

00:03:56.000 --> 00:04:00.600
Now, that outflow might well
trigger another thunderstorm.

00:04:00.600 --> 00:04:02.900
So that doesn't mean, for
example, over the state of

00:04:02.900 --> 00:04:05.800
Connecticut on a day when there
are thunderstorms, it

00:04:05.800 --> 00:04:09.133
doesn't mean there's just going
to be one and then none.

00:04:09.133 --> 00:04:11.367
It means there'll be one, and
then as it dies, it may

00:04:11.367 --> 00:04:13.567
trigger two others, and
then as they die,

00:04:13.567 --> 00:04:15.467
they may trigger others.

00:04:15.467 --> 00:04:18.700
So this may go on throughout
the afternoon, but the

00:04:18.700 --> 00:04:23.667
individual cells have
a short lifetime.

00:04:23.667 --> 00:04:25.300
That's an important
characteristic.

00:04:25.300 --> 00:04:31.167
As opposed to these severe
storms, which have the

00:04:31.167 --> 00:04:37.133
additional environmental factor
of having wind shear

00:04:37.133 --> 00:04:41.333
through the troposphere, usually
a jet stream aloft.

00:04:41.333 --> 00:04:43.733
Strong winds near the
tropopause, weak winds near

00:04:43.733 --> 00:04:47.567
the surface of the Earth, that
tends to bend the storm over

00:04:47.567 --> 00:04:53.067
and change its structure into
one in which the inflow is at

00:04:53.067 --> 00:04:56.267
a different location than the
outflow caused by that

00:04:56.267 --> 00:04:57.467
evaporative cooling.

00:04:57.467 --> 00:05:01.333
In fact, the cold air generated
by evaporative

00:05:01.333 --> 00:05:05.333
cooling spreads out and actually
forms a gust front

00:05:05.333 --> 00:05:07.933
over which the warm
air then lifts.

00:05:07.933 --> 00:05:11.500
So it actually assists in the
lifting of the warm air up

00:05:11.500 --> 00:05:12.433
into the cloud.

00:05:12.433 --> 00:05:16.467
And this structure is more or
less stable and can persist

00:05:16.467 --> 00:05:18.500
for a number of hours
and in some cases

00:05:18.500 --> 00:05:21.133
even for even overnight.

00:05:21.133 --> 00:05:23.067
And these are the
ones that have--

00:05:23.067 --> 00:05:25.433
they're larger and
they're severe in

00:05:25.433 --> 00:05:27.067
every way you can imagine.

00:05:27.067 --> 00:05:29.833
I think I showed these
last time.

00:05:29.833 --> 00:05:31.967
But heavy rains and
flooding, hail,

00:05:31.967 --> 00:05:34.367
lightning, tornadic winds.

00:05:34.367 --> 00:05:38.267
I don't think the low pressure
in the tornado is much of an

00:05:38.267 --> 00:05:41.667
issue, but the gust-front winds
coming from that cool

00:05:41.667 --> 00:05:45.900
air is another source
of wind damage.

00:05:45.900 --> 00:05:49.200
In many-- in some cases, that
causes more damage than even a

00:05:49.200 --> 00:05:50.167
tornado could.

00:05:50.167 --> 00:05:53.767
Usually, the tornadic winds are
stronger when there is a

00:05:53.767 --> 00:05:58.667
tornado, but the gust-front
winds may cover a wider area

00:05:58.667 --> 00:06:00.667
and in some cases will
cause more damage

00:06:00.667 --> 00:06:03.567
than a possible tornado.

00:06:06.833 --> 00:06:09.733
I don't know if I got
this far, but here's

00:06:09.733 --> 00:06:10.567
a picture of one.

00:06:10.567 --> 00:06:13.433
And earlier in the course, we
talked about the visual

00:06:13.433 --> 00:06:17.167
appearance of a funnel.

00:06:17.167 --> 00:06:19.367
And this is called the
condensation funnel.

00:06:19.367 --> 00:06:26.967
That is basically a cloud
composed of tiny liquid water

00:06:26.967 --> 00:06:34.000
droplets that's produced when
air from outside moves in and

00:06:34.000 --> 00:06:35.033
drops its pressure.

00:06:35.033 --> 00:06:40.067
The pressure inside a tornado
is much lower than in the

00:06:40.067 --> 00:06:42.600
surrounding atmosphere, so that
air that moves in there

00:06:42.600 --> 00:06:46.533
is going to expand, not by
moving vertically, but by

00:06:46.533 --> 00:06:48.667
moving into the tornado.

00:06:48.667 --> 00:06:51.900
It'll expand, cool, and
you can form a cloud.

00:06:51.900 --> 00:06:52.833
And that's what you're seeing.

00:06:52.833 --> 00:06:55.800
In fact, you often see this
descending from cloud base.

00:06:55.800 --> 00:06:59.167
The cloud base will appear to
be flat, and then as the

00:06:59.167 --> 00:07:01.867
tornado develops, that
funnel cloud will

00:07:01.867 --> 00:07:03.400
descend to the ground.

00:07:03.400 --> 00:07:06.633
When you see that, it's more
natural to understand that

00:07:06.633 --> 00:07:09.233
it's really like a cloud,
because it's actually an

00:07:09.233 --> 00:07:12.833
extension of that cloud reaching
down to the surface.

00:07:12.833 --> 00:07:15.200
Whereas this other thing here
is the debris funnel.

00:07:15.200 --> 00:07:19.400
That's stuff that's been kicked
up by the high winds at

00:07:19.400 --> 00:07:21.367
the surface, and that's
not water.

00:07:21.367 --> 00:07:26.067
That's usually dirt or soil or
cows or cars or houses and

00:07:26.067 --> 00:07:27.300
things like that.

00:07:29.433 --> 00:07:33.000
And here again, you see the
condensation funnel, and you

00:07:33.000 --> 00:07:35.967
see a debris funnel
around that.

00:07:39.300 --> 00:07:41.033
Lightning comes along
with that.

00:07:41.033 --> 00:07:45.667
And of course, these sparks of
electricity is what you hear

00:07:45.667 --> 00:07:46.900
as thunder.

00:07:49.300 --> 00:07:51.633
And I think you know that-- how
many know how to compute

00:07:51.633 --> 00:07:53.633
in your mind how
far a storm is?

00:07:53.633 --> 00:07:56.133
Do you know that trick?

00:07:56.133 --> 00:07:59.133
It's pretty simple, because you
assume that the light that

00:07:59.133 --> 00:08:04.233
comes from the lightning strike
travels to your eye at

00:08:04.233 --> 00:08:07.000
the speed of light, which
is, you might say,

00:08:07.000 --> 00:08:09.667
instantaneous, right?

00:08:09.667 --> 00:08:15.600
Whereas the sound that reaches
your ear moves at the speed of

00:08:15.600 --> 00:08:19.600
sound, which is something like
300 meters per second.

00:08:19.600 --> 00:08:23.733
And so if you simply-- when you
see a lightning flash, if

00:08:23.733 --> 00:08:27.367
you then count out the
number of seconds--

00:08:27.367 --> 00:08:29.100
one second, two seconds--

00:08:29.100 --> 00:08:33.533
so for every second delay
between the two, that's 300

00:08:33.533 --> 00:08:34.567
meters of distance.

00:08:34.567 --> 00:08:38.767
So if it was three seconds
delayed, that would be 900

00:08:38.767 --> 00:08:41.400
meters or about a kilometer
away from you.

00:08:41.400 --> 00:08:45.033
So that's an easy calculation
to do, realizing that the

00:08:45.033 --> 00:08:48.900
thunder is produced by
the lightning itself.

00:08:48.900 --> 00:08:52.833
You suddenly heat that air with
the electrical discharge,

00:08:52.833 --> 00:08:57.467
it expands suddenly, produces
an acoustic signal that then

00:08:57.467 --> 00:09:03.667
travels to your ear, and you
recognize that as thunder.

00:09:03.667 --> 00:09:04.900
Questions on that?

00:09:07.800 --> 00:09:12.567
Hailstones, because there's a
lot of supercooled water above

00:09:12.567 --> 00:09:16.267
the freezing line in those
storms and very strong updraft

00:09:16.267 --> 00:09:19.533
motions that can suspend
particles while

00:09:19.533 --> 00:09:22.367
they grow by riming.

00:09:22.367 --> 00:09:26.200
And eventually, when either that
updraft weakens or the

00:09:26.200 --> 00:09:28.400
object becomes too
large, it'll then

00:09:28.400 --> 00:09:29.567
fall out of the sky.

00:09:29.567 --> 00:09:32.667
And it's too large to melt.

00:09:32.667 --> 00:09:36.033
I told you many times that a
snowflake will melt as it

00:09:36.033 --> 00:09:37.900
passes down through
the freezing level

00:09:37.900 --> 00:09:39.300
and become a raindrop.

00:09:39.300 --> 00:09:43.533
But if I've got a chunk of ice
that's five centimeters across

00:09:43.533 --> 00:09:45.900
and it falls down,
it's too big.

00:09:45.900 --> 00:09:48.733
It's going to take
minutes to melt.

00:09:48.733 --> 00:09:51.367
And by that time, it'll
be at the surface.

00:09:51.367 --> 00:09:55.833
It'll be wet, it'll have a wet
outer surface, but it'll still

00:09:55.833 --> 00:09:59.767
be a solid chunk of ice when
it falls to Earth and hits.

00:10:05.467 --> 00:10:08.967
This is thunderstorm frequency
across the United States,

00:10:08.967 --> 00:10:12.133
number of thunderstorms
per year.

00:10:12.133 --> 00:10:13.667
Now, I've told you that
these are called--

00:10:13.667 --> 00:10:16.400
most of these are just air-mass
thunderstorms.

00:10:16.400 --> 00:10:18.867
They're not so damaging.

00:10:18.867 --> 00:10:24.067
And it looks like Florida is
the capital for air-mass

00:10:24.067 --> 00:10:28.433
thunderstorms. You get
100 of them per year.

00:10:28.433 --> 00:10:31.800
Other areas get far less.

00:10:31.800 --> 00:10:33.267
But these aren't the
severe ones.

00:10:33.267 --> 00:10:35.667
I'll show you the severe
ones in just a moment.

00:10:35.667 --> 00:10:37.833
You don't get many thunderstorms
in the West

00:10:37.833 --> 00:10:43.467
Coast, because there's too
strong an inversion there.

00:10:43.467 --> 00:10:46.533
Theres a temp-- normally, with
the cold water off the coast

00:10:46.533 --> 00:10:49.633
from the California Current,
the atmosphere over here is

00:10:49.633 --> 00:10:54.567
just too stable, too many
inversions to get

00:10:54.567 --> 00:10:57.700
thunderstorms forming in
that part of the world.

00:10:57.700 --> 00:11:00.133
So it really is kind of an
East Coast phenomenon.

00:11:00.133 --> 00:11:03.000
But it starts right at the Rocky
Mountain Front here in

00:11:03.000 --> 00:11:07.267
Colorado, and you find storms
then pretty much all the way

00:11:07.267 --> 00:11:09.733
to the east, including all the
way up into Canada you get

00:11:09.733 --> 00:11:12.467
quite a few.

00:11:12.467 --> 00:11:17.433
Now, I don't often in this
course talk about the research

00:11:17.433 --> 00:11:21.167
that goes on here at Yale or in
my group, but I wanted to

00:11:21.167 --> 00:11:22.933
show you one thing.

00:11:22.933 --> 00:11:26.233
I had a Ph.D. Student who
finished a couple of years ago

00:11:26.233 --> 00:11:30.400
who tried to understand the
timing of thunderstorms from

00:11:30.400 --> 00:11:32.100
west to east across--

00:11:32.100 --> 00:11:34.833
in a region generally
like this.

00:11:34.833 --> 00:11:38.600
And so she looked at
a lot of climate--

00:11:38.600 --> 00:11:44.200
of rainfall data from the summer
months and came up with

00:11:44.200 --> 00:11:45.233
a diagram like this.

00:11:45.233 --> 00:11:46.333
Now, I'm going to
explain this.

00:11:46.333 --> 00:11:48.567
It's going to take a minute just
to figure out what in the

00:11:48.567 --> 00:11:49.867
heck is plotted here.

00:11:49.867 --> 00:11:52.300
But on this axis is longitude.

00:11:52.300 --> 00:11:57.267
So it's distance east-west
basically through a region

00:11:57.267 --> 00:11:58.200
something like this.

00:11:58.200 --> 00:12:01.233
So it's the distance east-west
in a latitude belt

00:12:01.233 --> 00:12:03.400
something like that.

00:12:03.400 --> 00:12:07.367
And on this axis is the
local solar time.

00:12:07.367 --> 00:12:10.867
So instead of actually using
time zones, which are kind of

00:12:10.867 --> 00:12:12.500
an artificial construct--

00:12:12.500 --> 00:12:15.533
they make arbitrary choices
about where to switch from

00:12:15.533 --> 00:12:18.200
Eastern Time to Central Time
to Mountain Time--

00:12:18.200 --> 00:12:19.433
this is just local time.

00:12:19.433 --> 00:12:23.000
Basically, how high is the sun
in the sky, that determines

00:12:23.000 --> 00:12:25.567
what this clock would be.

00:12:25.567 --> 00:12:29.400
And then contoured is the
precipitation rate, the hourly

00:12:29.400 --> 00:12:30.967
precipitation rate.

00:12:30.967 --> 00:12:34.567
So from this diagram, for any
given latitude, if you scan

00:12:34.567 --> 00:12:37.233
up, you'll find how much
it rains at different

00:12:37.233 --> 00:12:38.167
hours of the day.

00:12:38.167 --> 00:12:40.267
Now, we did repeat.

00:12:40.267 --> 00:12:41.933
We plotted everything twice.

00:12:41.933 --> 00:12:45.367
So you've got zero to 24
and then 24 to 48.

00:12:45.367 --> 00:12:48.367
But if you notice, the plot
just repeats as well.

00:12:48.367 --> 00:12:51.467
So we've just put the same data
on there twice, which

00:12:51.467 --> 00:12:53.633
makes it a little bit
easier to go through

00:12:53.633 --> 00:12:55.833
a full day's cycle.

00:12:55.833 --> 00:12:59.400
You can start at any hour you
want and go 24 hours ahead.

00:12:59.400 --> 00:13:01.567
So this is the Rocky
Mountain Front.

00:13:01.567 --> 00:13:06.200
This is where a lot of
thunderstorms form.

00:13:06.200 --> 00:13:08.167
It's over in here.

00:13:08.167 --> 00:13:14.500
And those storms tend to form
between 1200 and 1800.

00:13:14.500 --> 00:13:17.533
So that's in the afternoon,
local solar time.

00:13:17.533 --> 00:13:18.933
Now, that's not a
surprise, right?

00:13:18.933 --> 00:13:21.500
Because one of the most
important triggers for

00:13:21.500 --> 00:13:26.367
thunderstorms is the heating
of the Earth by the Sun.

00:13:26.367 --> 00:13:30.467
So it's in the afternoon when
you've built up this deep

00:13:30.467 --> 00:13:32.867
convective boundary layer
by heating the

00:13:32.867 --> 00:13:34.067
surface of the Earth.

00:13:34.067 --> 00:13:37.367
And finally, that heating is
going to generate cumulus

00:13:37.367 --> 00:13:40.033
clouds, and they'll then grow
to form cumulonimbus.

00:13:40.033 --> 00:13:42.567
So it's not surprising
that you find

00:13:42.567 --> 00:13:43.967
storms beginning there.

00:13:43.967 --> 00:13:46.933
And over the East Coast-- here
in Connecticut, for example--

00:13:46.933 --> 00:13:53.667
you also find that the storms
form in the afternoon, due to

00:13:53.667 --> 00:13:55.267
the heating of the
Earth by the Sun.

00:13:55.267 --> 00:14:00.700
But look what happens in this
middle territory, which is

00:14:00.700 --> 00:14:04.800
basically this very large
region through here.

00:14:04.800 --> 00:14:07.367
That has some other kind of a
trigger, because, look, that

00:14:07.367 --> 00:14:09.367
is advancing in time.

00:14:09.367 --> 00:14:14.000
As I move eastward, the time
of day when thunderstorms

00:14:14.000 --> 00:14:18.933
occur is 6 o'clock, 9 o'clock
in the evening, midnight, 3

00:14:18.933 --> 00:14:21.633
o'clock in the morning,
6 o'clock the next

00:14:21.633 --> 00:14:22.567
morning, and so on.

00:14:22.567 --> 00:14:25.767
So you've got something that is
departing from the simple

00:14:25.767 --> 00:14:29.467
idea of the Sun as the
driving force.

00:14:29.467 --> 00:14:33.100
What this turns out to be is a
disturbance that's generated

00:14:33.100 --> 00:14:36.600
each day over the Rocky
Mountains and then is--

00:14:36.600 --> 00:14:38.467
whoops, wrong direction--

00:14:38.467 --> 00:14:42.933
and then is pushed eastwards
by the westerly winds.

00:14:42.933 --> 00:14:46.100
And it's a warm air disturbance

00:14:46.100 --> 00:14:47.367
generated over the mountains.

00:14:47.367 --> 00:14:51.000
And as it drifts eastward
aloft, it triggers

00:14:51.000 --> 00:14:54.233
thunderstorms as
it moves along.

00:14:54.233 --> 00:14:56.800
I had somebody in my office
a couple of weeks ago, a

00:14:56.800 --> 00:15:01.433
scientist who grew up in one
of these states and always

00:15:01.433 --> 00:15:05.200
wondered why there they had a
maximum thunderstorm frequency

00:15:05.200 --> 00:15:06.067
in the middle of the night.

00:15:06.067 --> 00:15:07.100
Who would expect that?

00:15:07.100 --> 00:15:10.700
It doesn't seem to fit with
the standard thermal solar

00:15:10.700 --> 00:15:11.467
forcing idea.

00:15:11.467 --> 00:15:12.333
Well, this is why.

00:15:12.333 --> 00:15:15.067
In this case, my student
discovered that it's a

00:15:15.067 --> 00:15:17.933
disturbance generated over the
Rockies that moves eastward

00:15:17.933 --> 00:15:21.867
and gives that progressive
timing to the thunderstorms.

00:15:21.867 --> 00:15:25.233
Then you get east of the
Appalachian Mountains, and you

00:15:25.233 --> 00:15:28.767
get back to a more normal
mid-afternoon

00:15:28.767 --> 00:15:30.967
thunderstorm maxima.

00:15:30.967 --> 00:15:32.667
Any questions on that?

00:15:32.667 --> 00:15:34.900
STUDENT: What are those
dotted lines?

00:15:34.900 --> 00:15:36.800
PROFESSOR: I think
they're reference lines

00:15:36.800 --> 00:15:41.100
for some other figure in the
paper that's not shown here.

00:15:41.100 --> 00:15:44.000
So there are sloping lines
that are drawn in here at

00:15:44.000 --> 00:15:45.100
different speeds.

00:15:45.100 --> 00:15:49.800
Since this is distance versus
time, a slope represents a

00:15:49.800 --> 00:15:51.500
propagation speed--

00:15:51.500 --> 00:15:54.500
30 meters per second, 14 meters
per second, seven

00:15:54.500 --> 00:15:55.467
meters per second.

00:15:55.467 --> 00:15:58.933
These disturbances move eastward
at about 14 meters

00:15:58.933 --> 00:16:03.100
per second, bringing those
thunderstorms progressively

00:16:03.100 --> 00:16:04.100
later as you move

00:16:04.100 --> 00:16:05.967
towards the east. Yes.

00:16:05.967 --> 00:16:09.467
STUDENT: Was it already known
that there was a warm weather

00:16:09.467 --> 00:16:13.133
air disturbance over
the Rockies, or did

00:16:13.133 --> 00:16:13.700
she figure that out?

00:16:13.700 --> 00:16:15.967
PROFESSOR: No, that's not shown in this

00:16:15.967 --> 00:16:17.267
figure, but that
was actually--

00:16:17.267 --> 00:16:21.267
there was some hint about this
progression already from radar

00:16:21.267 --> 00:16:24.667
data, but she confirmed
it using surface data.

00:16:24.667 --> 00:16:27.667
And then she discovered this
warm air pulse aloft that was

00:16:27.667 --> 00:16:29.500
doing the triggering.

00:16:29.500 --> 00:16:32.833
That was the point of
her thesis, yeah.

00:16:32.833 --> 00:16:34.400
Anything else on that?

00:16:37.733 --> 00:16:40.700
So now let's get to the severe
thunderstorms. And the way

00:16:40.700 --> 00:16:43.567
I'll get at that is just to
show you this tornado

00:16:43.567 --> 00:16:46.667
frequency map.

00:16:46.667 --> 00:16:48.100
And of course, it looks
a bit different.

00:16:48.100 --> 00:16:52.067
There is a maximum in Florida,
but it's smaller.

00:16:52.067 --> 00:16:55.733
And the big maximum
is over Texas,

00:16:55.733 --> 00:16:58.300
Oklahoma, Kansas, Nebraska.

00:16:58.300 --> 00:17:01.800
And of course, this is
what's called Tornado

00:17:01.800 --> 00:17:03.167
Alley by some people.

00:17:03.167 --> 00:17:04.467
You've heard that expression.

00:17:04.467 --> 00:17:05.233
It's kind of the region.

00:17:05.233 --> 00:17:08.033
But what's special about this
region apparently-- and by the

00:17:08.033 --> 00:17:11.433
way, this maximizes
in the spring.

00:17:11.433 --> 00:17:16.800
So typically, this is an
April-May phenomenon.

00:17:16.800 --> 00:17:20.100
If you have watched any of
these shows about chasing

00:17:20.100 --> 00:17:23.767
tornadoes and if you want to
do that, then schedule your

00:17:23.767 --> 00:17:27.700
trip in April and May, because
that's when things get

00:17:27.700 --> 00:17:29.733
exciting out there.

00:17:29.733 --> 00:17:33.467
And what's special about this
region is that you get some

00:17:33.467 --> 00:17:36.700
warm, moist air moving in from
the Gulf of Mexico at low

00:17:36.700 --> 00:17:40.800
levels, and then you get the jet
stream coming across the

00:17:40.800 --> 00:17:42.733
Rocky Mountains at
high levels.

00:17:42.733 --> 00:17:46.300
And that gives you the
shear that you need.

00:17:46.300 --> 00:17:48.800
And you've got the moisture,
because you've got the high

00:17:48.800 --> 00:17:51.433
temperatures and high humidities
in the low levels.

00:17:51.433 --> 00:17:54.267
So all the ingredients
are kind of there.

00:17:54.267 --> 00:17:57.067
Not every day-- it fluctuates
from day to day-- but

00:17:57.067 --> 00:18:00.400
generally, that's the reason why
this area is so special.

00:18:00.400 --> 00:18:04.733
And as far as I know, there's
no other place on Earth that

00:18:04.733 --> 00:18:08.100
has as many-- as high a tornado
frequency as this

00:18:08.100 --> 00:18:08.700
region does.

00:18:08.700 --> 00:18:11.633
So this is special even
if you look globally.

00:18:11.633 --> 00:18:15.400
There are a few other places in
Asia and in Australia where

00:18:15.400 --> 00:18:18.700
they get this phenomenon, but
this is kind of the most

00:18:18.700 --> 00:18:23.467
frequent place for
it to occur.

