For example, I read a paper once
about this one, who tried

00:18:47.433 --> 00:18:51.300
to claim there was something
special about the terrain in

00:18:51.300 --> 00:18:52.133
that region.

00:18:52.133 --> 00:18:54.600
But to be honest with you, I
would doubt the statistical

00:18:54.600 --> 00:18:57.667
significance of something like
that, unless I really had seen

00:18:57.667 --> 00:19:00.867
a very rigorous statistical
analysis.

00:19:00.867 --> 00:19:04.433
I would wonder whether these
spots are really realistic or

00:19:04.433 --> 00:19:07.067
whether they're just a fluke
of what-- and he had one or

00:19:07.067 --> 00:19:10.200
two events there, and by random
chance, that happened

00:19:10.200 --> 00:19:12.300
to look like a little maximum
or something like that.

00:19:12.300 --> 00:19:16.800
So I wouldn't try to put too
much significance on those.

00:19:16.800 --> 00:19:18.433
Whether that-- that may be
distinct from this one.

00:19:18.433 --> 00:19:20.800
I think the case could
be made there.

00:19:20.800 --> 00:19:22.267
But I'm not sure why.

00:19:22.267 --> 00:19:27.267
I'm not sure why there would
be two maxima there.

00:19:27.267 --> 00:19:31.200
We do get them in Connecticut
as well.

00:19:31.200 --> 00:19:33.967
Not frequently, but every few
years, we get a tornado that

00:19:33.967 --> 00:19:35.200
comes down through the state.

00:19:35.200 --> 00:19:38.167
It can cause quite
a bit of damage.

00:19:38.167 --> 00:19:42.667
But it's like a ratio of 7:1
or 9:1 in terms of the

00:19:42.667 --> 00:19:47.700
