00:26:35.333 --> 00:26:37.000
It's fascinating stuff.

00:26:37.000 --> 00:26:39.433
And we'll turn to hurricanes.

00:26:42.000 --> 00:26:45.400
Now, a few basic bullet points
about hurricanes.

00:26:45.400 --> 00:26:48.700
As with other convective storms,
they get their energy

00:26:48.700 --> 00:26:51.367
from latent heat release.

00:26:51.367 --> 00:26:54.900
In this case, they get
that water vapor

00:26:54.900 --> 00:26:57.133
directly from the ocean.

00:26:57.133 --> 00:27:03.767
So it doesn't-- you don't use
up the water vapor in the

00:27:03.767 --> 00:27:09.667
atmosphere as a tornado begins
to draw on it, because with a

00:27:09.667 --> 00:27:13.233
warm ocean, you can evaporate
water from the ocean just as

00:27:13.233 --> 00:27:15.867
fast as you're drawing
it up in the storm.

00:27:15.867 --> 00:27:19.667
So in one way, it's better to
say that really it's the warm

00:27:19.667 --> 00:27:24.867
ocean that provides the fuel
for this, but yet it's also

00:27:24.867 --> 00:27:25.500
water vapor.

00:27:25.500 --> 00:27:29.800
The warm water evaporates, and
then you get the water vapor

00:27:29.800 --> 00:27:30.933
that goes up into the cloud.

00:27:30.933 --> 00:27:34.000
And as it rises, you get the
latent heat release and the

00:27:34.000 --> 00:27:36.567
buoyancy and so on
and so forth.

00:27:36.567 --> 00:27:39.733
Now, if you have too
much wind shear--

00:27:39.733 --> 00:27:43.100
this is just the opposite of
the severe thunderstorm.

00:27:43.100 --> 00:27:46.900
Severe thunderstorms require
that wind shear to distort it

00:27:46.900 --> 00:27:50.867
and give it that severe
condition, whereas hurricanes

00:27:50.867 --> 00:27:53.233
out over the ocean, if you have
a lot of wind shear, they

00:27:53.233 --> 00:27:54.700
will not form.

00:27:54.700 --> 00:27:58.967
They're a symmetric kind of
deal, and if you try to shear

00:27:58.967 --> 00:28:00.833
that off, you'll just
destroy it.

00:28:00.833 --> 00:28:04.167
So you need a lot of warm ocean
water and not very much

00:28:04.167 --> 00:28:08.300
shear, and then you can, under
some conditions, you can

00:28:08.300 --> 00:28:10.933
generate a hurricane.

00:28:10.933 --> 00:28:12.967
They cannot form at the Equator,
because they have to

00:28:12.967 --> 00:28:17.033
spin one way or the other, and
they get that cue from the

00:28:17.033 --> 00:28:18.800
Coriolis force.

00:28:18.800 --> 00:28:20.967
And so if there's no
Coriolis force, you

00:28:20.967 --> 00:28:23.133
cannot form a hurricane.

00:28:23.133 --> 00:28:24.667
So they cannot form
at the Equator.

00:28:24.667 --> 00:28:27.067
And as I mentioned the other
day, they cannot even cross

00:28:27.067 --> 00:28:28.133
the Equator.

00:28:28.133 --> 00:28:30.133
Once they've formed in one
hemisphere, they've got to

00:28:30.133 --> 00:28:31.000
stay in that hemisphere.

00:28:31.000 --> 00:28:34.367
They can't suddenly decide to
wander across to the other

00:28:34.367 --> 00:28:34.800
hemisphere.

00:28:34.800 --> 00:28:39.800
They couldn't exist with the
spin that they have. They do

00:28:39.800 --> 00:28:43.433
spin oppositely in the
two hemispheres.

00:28:43.433 --> 00:28:46.733
Just like in the tornado, the
pressure is very low in the

00:28:46.733 --> 00:28:51.567
center, and that balances the
Coriolis force and the

00:28:51.567 --> 00:28:54.933
centripetal force of the air
spinning around the outside.

00:28:54.933 --> 00:28:58.533
So this is a cyclone in the
same sense that I defined

00:28:58.533 --> 00:29:00.967
cyclone for you the other day.

00:29:00.967 --> 00:29:05.600
It's a low-pressure center
with air currents moving

00:29:05.600 --> 00:29:07.600
around it in a cyclonic
direction--

00:29:07.600 --> 00:29:09.867
that is, counterclockwise in
the Northern Hemisphere,

00:29:09.867 --> 00:29:13.300
clockwise in the Southern
Hemisphere.

00:29:13.300 --> 00:29:15.867
They occur in the late summer
and early fall in both

00:29:15.867 --> 00:29:17.667
hemispheres.

00:29:17.667 --> 00:29:24.667
Be careful how you use those
terms. On land, the highest

00:29:24.667 --> 00:29:29.367
temperatures normally occur four
to six weeks after the

00:29:29.367 --> 00:29:31.000
summer solstice.

00:29:31.000 --> 00:29:34.800
The summer solstice
is about June 21.

00:29:34.800 --> 00:29:40.233
The warmest days of summer are
usually mid-July for air over

00:29:40.233 --> 00:29:41.667
the continents.

00:29:41.667 --> 00:29:45.367
But oceans have more heat
capacity, and they take a

00:29:45.367 --> 00:29:47.767
longer time to warm up.

00:29:47.767 --> 00:29:51.400
So the warmer ocean temperatures
occur almost

00:29:51.400 --> 00:29:55.467
three months after the
summer solstice.

00:29:55.467 --> 00:29:58.833
The warmest ocean temperatures
typically are in August,

00:29:58.833 --> 00:30:00.367
September, and October.

00:30:00.367 --> 00:30:04.433
And since the hurricanes need
that, they need warm ocean

00:30:04.433 --> 00:30:09.767
temperatures, the hurricane
season is then delayed that

00:30:09.767 --> 00:30:10.267
three months.

00:30:10.267 --> 00:30:12.600
So it's not midsummer
or early summer.

00:30:12.600 --> 00:30:15.267
It's late summer and early fall,
because that's when the

00:30:15.267 --> 00:30:16.600
ocean's sea surface
temperature--

00:30:16.600 --> 00:30:20.967
SST is the abbreviation for
sea surface temperature--

00:30:20.967 --> 00:30:24.267
is the highest. That
defines the

00:30:24.267 --> 00:30:25.633
so-called hurricane season.

00:30:25.633 --> 00:30:28.300
Now remember, in the Northern
Hemisphere, that is going to

00:30:28.300 --> 00:30:33.867
be July, August, September,
and maybe a little bit in

00:30:33.867 --> 00:30:39.433
October, whereas in the Southern
Hemisphere, that is

00:30:39.433 --> 00:30:43.967
going to be, well, January,
February, March, and April in

00:30:43.967 --> 00:30:45.100
the Southern Hemisphere.

00:30:45.100 --> 00:30:47.900
That's their summertime, and
that's when hurricanes are

00:30:47.900 --> 00:30:52.100
going to be most frequent in
the Southern Hemisphere.

00:30:52.100 --> 00:30:56.067
They tend to drift westward,
because they occur in the

00:30:56.067 --> 00:31:01.167
tropics under the influence
of the trade winds.

00:31:01.167 --> 00:31:04.467
It's like you had a stream of
water and you dip your hand in

00:31:04.467 --> 00:31:07.233
and made a little vortex, and
you would watch and see that

00:31:07.233 --> 00:31:10.867
that vortex is just carried
along by the stream.

00:31:10.867 --> 00:31:13.600
Whatever direction the stream is
going in, that vortex would

00:31:13.600 --> 00:31:14.567
move as well.

00:31:14.567 --> 00:31:20.600
And that's primarily what's
going on when tornado is--

00:31:20.600 --> 00:31:22.200
when a hurricane is
moving westward.

00:31:22.200 --> 00:31:26.033
However, it also has a poleward
drift that can't be

00:31:26.033 --> 00:31:29.967
explained as simply as that, and
that has something to do

00:31:29.967 --> 00:31:31.233
with the curvature
of the Earth.

00:31:31.233 --> 00:31:33.167
I've published on this,
but I don't have time

00:31:33.167 --> 00:31:33.733
to go through it.

00:31:33.733 --> 00:31:40.633
But there is a drift of
hurricanes toward the pole in

00:31:40.633 --> 00:31:42.133
both hemispheres--

00:31:42.133 --> 00:31:44.933
the North Pole in the Northern
Hemisphere, the South Pole in

00:31:44.933 --> 00:31:46.600
the Southern Hemisphere--

00:31:46.600 --> 00:31:51.267
that is added to that general
westward drift due to being in

00:31:51.267 --> 00:31:53.167
the belt of the easterly
trade winds.

00:31:56.233 --> 00:32:01.733
So these are the global
hurricane tracks.

00:32:01.733 --> 00:32:04.967
It's interesting for what is in
this diagram and what's not

00:32:04.967 --> 00:32:05.700
in this diagram.

00:32:05.700 --> 00:32:09.667
For example, in the North
Atlantic Ocean--

00:32:09.667 --> 00:32:12.800
the Equator is about here--

00:32:12.800 --> 00:32:16.967
generally, hurricanes form in
the central and sometimes even

00:32:16.967 --> 00:32:20.967
eastern part of the tropical
North Atlantic, and then they

00:32:20.967 --> 00:32:22.700
move westward and northward.

00:32:22.700 --> 00:32:26.567
So generally, they follow a
looping trajectory like this,

00:32:26.567 --> 00:32:29.933
or maybe they go straight into
the Gulf of Mexico or through

00:32:29.933 --> 00:32:34.300
the Caribbean into the Gulf
of Mexico like that.

00:32:34.300 --> 00:32:41.033
In the eastern tropical North
Pacific, you have a very high

00:32:41.033 --> 00:32:44.367
density of hurricanes.

00:32:44.367 --> 00:32:47.833
Most of these don't threaten
land, because they're going

00:32:47.833 --> 00:32:51.400
out to sea, but some of them
that move up along the coast

00:32:51.400 --> 00:32:53.400
can threaten land.

00:32:53.400 --> 00:32:55.433
They don't go very far north,
because there's a cold

00:32:55.433 --> 00:32:59.600
California Current that
comes down here.

00:32:59.600 --> 00:33:01.533
I didn't put this in the notes,
but you should write it

00:33:01.533 --> 00:33:04.967
down that many people think
there's a critical ocean

00:33:04.967 --> 00:33:08.900
temperature below which you
cannot have hurricanes.

00:33:08.900 --> 00:33:11.967
And some people will tell you
that's 27 degrees Celsius.

00:33:11.967 --> 00:33:14.367
Some people say it's
28 degrees Celsius.

00:33:14.367 --> 00:33:18.267
But somewhere about there is a
critical ocean temperature.

00:33:18.267 --> 00:33:21.200
And so the ocean has to be
warmer than, let's say, 28

00:33:21.200 --> 00:33:25.533
Celsius before it can
support a hurricane.

00:33:25.533 --> 00:33:28.900
And you don't have that up
here, because the cold

00:33:28.900 --> 00:33:31.033
California Current comes
down, but closer to

00:33:31.033 --> 00:33:32.133
the Equator you do.

00:33:32.133 --> 00:33:35.833
Notice, right at the Equator,
no hurricanes.

00:33:35.833 --> 00:33:40.300
Plenty of warm water, but
no Coriolis force, so no

00:33:40.300 --> 00:33:42.500
hurricanes.

00:33:42.500 --> 00:33:48.333
The western tropical North
Pacific is a hotbed-- the

00:33:48.333 --> 00:33:52.467
world's biggest hotbed
of hurricanes.

00:33:52.467 --> 00:33:54.500
Be careful, though.

00:33:54.500 --> 00:33:58.967
The word "hurricane"
traditionally is not used in

00:33:58.967 --> 00:34:00.233
that part of the world.

00:34:00.233 --> 00:34:04.900
These are normally referred to
as typhoons, after a Japanese

00:34:04.900 --> 00:34:09.067
word for "hurricane." So it
wouldn't be wrong to call

00:34:09.067 --> 00:34:12.767
these hurricanes, but it
wouldn't be the vernacular.

00:34:12.767 --> 00:34:15.033
The vernacular would
be typhoon.

00:34:15.033 --> 00:34:19.167
And so if I say there's a
typhoon in the Western

00:34:19.167 --> 00:34:20.967
Pacific, you'll know
I'm talking

00:34:20.967 --> 00:34:22.933
about a hurricane there.

00:34:22.933 --> 00:34:25.700
And they've got the same kind of
pattern as in the Atlantic.

00:34:25.700 --> 00:34:29.167
They go westward, but they
also arc northwards.

00:34:29.167 --> 00:34:33.033
In the Indian Ocean, you get
some in the Arabian Sea and

00:34:33.033 --> 00:34:35.067
the Bay of Bengal.

00:34:35.067 --> 00:34:37.100
Not many, but you do
get some, and they

00:34:37.100 --> 00:34:38.767
can be quite damaging.

00:34:38.767 --> 00:34:40.400
In the Southern Hemisphere,
look at this.

00:34:40.400 --> 00:34:41.800
You get them in the
Indian Ocean.

00:34:41.800 --> 00:34:44.567
You get them in the west
tropical Pacific.

00:34:44.567 --> 00:34:49.633
You don't get them in
the east at all.

00:34:49.633 --> 00:34:55.867
And I would've said you don't
get them in the Atlantic, but

00:34:55.867 --> 00:34:57.333
there was one about
four years ago.

00:34:57.333 --> 00:35:01.700
It was the first-ever reported
hurricane in the tropical

00:35:01.700 --> 00:35:04.600
South Pacific, and they've got
that one marked in here.

00:35:04.600 --> 00:35:06.367
Now, this is pretty
easy to explain.

00:35:06.367 --> 00:35:08.300
There's a cold current--

00:35:08.300 --> 00:35:10.567
it's called the Humboldt
Current,

00:35:10.567 --> 00:35:12.600
after a German explorer--

00:35:12.600 --> 00:35:14.967
a cold current that comes up
along the coast of South

00:35:14.967 --> 00:35:22.167
America and floods this part
of the southern eastward

00:35:22.167 --> 00:35:24.100
tropical Pacific.

00:35:24.100 --> 00:35:25.767
And therefore, the temperatures
are not warm

00:35:25.767 --> 00:35:27.967
enough to support hurricanes.

00:35:27.967 --> 00:35:30.267
And pretty much the same
thing is true here.

00:35:30.267 --> 00:35:33.733
There's a cold current that
comes up along here.

00:35:33.733 --> 00:35:37.500
And while there is some warm air
right-- some water right

00:35:37.500 --> 00:35:41.200
along the Equator, there you
don't have the Coriolis force.

00:35:41.200 --> 00:35:43.533
And here you've got the Coriolis
force, but the

00:35:43.533 --> 00:35:44.600
temperatures are too low.

00:35:44.600 --> 00:35:47.667
So you're not getting those two
ingredients together, the

00:35:47.667 --> 00:35:51.367
warm water and the
Coriolis force.

00:35:51.367 --> 00:35:54.300
Questions on this diagram?

00:35:54.300 --> 00:35:58.133
Remember, these are not
occurring simultaneously.

00:35:58.133 --> 00:36:01.200
This is in Northern Hemisphere
hurricane season.

00:36:01.200 --> 00:36:04.000
These are in Southern Hemisphere
hurricane season.

00:36:04.000 --> 00:36:09.667
We've just put them all together
on one diagram there.

00:36:09.667 --> 00:36:15.667
So here's a zoom in of
the Atlantic Ocean.

00:36:15.667 --> 00:36:19.433
And you can see that
many of them come--

00:36:19.433 --> 00:36:22.500
so once a hurricane gets
started, it's going to

00:36:22.500 --> 00:36:26.967
persist. It's a good,
stable storm system.

00:36:26.967 --> 00:36:28.900
It'll persist until
the conditions no

00:36:28.900 --> 00:36:31.033
longer make it possible.

00:36:31.033 --> 00:36:34.000
One of two things will happen.

00:36:34.000 --> 00:36:37.467
It'll move over land, in which
case it no longer has that

00:36:37.467 --> 00:36:42.067
water supply, or it'll move over
cold water, in which case

00:36:42.067 --> 00:36:44.400
it no longer has enough
water supply.

00:36:44.400 --> 00:36:49.867
Because the water can't
evaporate fast enough from a

00:36:49.867 --> 00:36:51.100
cold ocean.

00:36:53.967 --> 00:36:57.900
Typically, from the satellite,
they look like this.

00:36:57.900 --> 00:37:01.867
They have a well-developed,
large cloud shield.

00:37:01.867 --> 00:37:04.867
It's like a thunderstorm anvil,
except it's kind of

00:37:04.867 --> 00:37:05.567
axisymmetric.

00:37:05.567 --> 00:37:09.767
That means moving out
in all directions.

00:37:09.767 --> 00:37:13.267
And very often, but not always,
there's an eye, which

00:37:13.267 --> 00:37:16.067
is a very peculiar
characteristic.

00:37:16.067 --> 00:37:20.233
The air everywhere else is
rising, but right there, the

00:37:20.233 --> 00:37:21.900
air is sinking.

00:37:21.900 --> 00:37:24.033
I know that because it's
clear of clouds.

00:37:24.033 --> 00:37:28.467
Clear of clouds means sinking
air, thermodynamically.

00:37:28.467 --> 00:37:34.500
Underneath this, you can't see
it, but the winds are strong

00:37:34.500 --> 00:37:37.200
in the cyclonic direction.

00:37:37.200 --> 00:37:41.867
So here's kind of a cartoonish
cross-section.

00:37:41.867 --> 00:37:44.000
You've got these rain bands.

00:37:44.000 --> 00:37:47.067
The rain is not uniform in a
hurricane but forms in these

00:37:47.067 --> 00:37:51.033
spiral, heavy-raining bands.

00:37:51.033 --> 00:37:54.800
The air rises in this main
eyewall and then spreads out

00:37:54.800 --> 00:37:56.667
in this giant anvil.

00:37:56.667 --> 00:37:59.333
First, it's still moving in
the cyclonic direction.

00:37:59.333 --> 00:38:02.167
When that air moves far enough
out, the Coriolis force acts

00:38:02.167 --> 00:38:05.733
on it and actually reverses
its sense of direction.

00:38:05.733 --> 00:38:06.433
So be careful.

00:38:06.433 --> 00:38:09.933
If you're looking at movies of
hurricanes, you may find that

00:38:09.933 --> 00:38:14.433
the outer clouds are actually
moving anticyclonically.

00:38:14.433 --> 00:38:15.733
Don't be confused.

00:38:15.733 --> 00:38:20.300
All the rest of the storm is
still a tight, cyclonically

00:38:20.300 --> 00:38:22.900
spinning vortex.

00:38:22.900 --> 00:38:26.300
And then a little bit of that
air that rises in the eyewall

00:38:26.300 --> 00:38:30.800
sinks right down in the eye and
keeps that little section

00:38:30.800 --> 00:38:32.567
clear of clouds.

00:38:32.567 --> 00:38:36.500
Most of it, however, spreads out
in this giant anvil, whose

00:38:36.500 --> 00:38:41.233
diameter is several hundred
kilometers across.

00:38:41.233 --> 00:38:44.100
So hurricane damage, of
course, wind impact on

00:38:44.100 --> 00:38:45.333
buildings and vegetation.

00:38:45.333 --> 00:38:48.700
Remember that the pressure
that a wind exerts on a

00:38:48.700 --> 00:38:53.933
surface is proportional to the
square of the wind speed.

00:38:53.933 --> 00:38:57.667
So if you have a 10 meter per
second wind hitting my house,

00:38:57.667 --> 00:38:59.400
that produces a certain force.

00:38:59.400 --> 00:39:02.900
If you have a 20 meters per
second, that's four times--

00:39:02.900 --> 00:39:06.233
twice the speed, but four
times the pressure force

00:39:06.233 --> 00:39:08.033
pushing on the house,
and so on.

00:39:08.033 --> 00:39:12.267
So if you have a hurricane
that's 60 meters per second or

00:39:12.267 --> 00:39:17.633
120 meters per second, the
destructive forces of that

00:39:17.633 --> 00:39:24.500
push really go up very, very
steeply and can destroy most

00:39:24.500 --> 00:39:27.300
buildings, unless they're
specially designed to be

00:39:27.300 --> 00:39:29.700
hurricane-secure.

00:39:29.700 --> 00:39:32.133
Another thing is that
storm surge.

00:39:32.133 --> 00:39:37.000
The rapid air movement across
the surface of the ocean

00:39:37.000 --> 00:39:41.267
pushes water towards the shore
and will give an apparent rise

00:39:41.267 --> 00:39:42.233
in sea level.

00:39:42.233 --> 00:39:45.533
We talked about this when we
were discussing Irene.

00:39:45.533 --> 00:39:48.667
And if you're standing on the
beach, the water just suddenly

00:39:48.667 --> 00:39:51.133
seems to rise and move inland.

00:39:51.133 --> 00:39:53.867
On top of that, there's going to
be the waves caused by the

00:39:53.867 --> 00:39:57.567
winds as well, but that storm
surge is often responsible for

00:39:57.567 --> 00:39:59.767
some of the major damage.

00:39:59.767 --> 00:40:02.100
Inland flooding as well, and
we saw that in Irene.

00:40:02.100 --> 00:40:05.967
Poor Vermont, and New Jersey to
some extent too, had a lot

00:40:05.967 --> 00:40:09.400
of rainfall, which collected
quickly into the valleys and

00:40:09.400 --> 00:40:12.933
rivers and caused a
lot of flooding.

00:40:12.933 --> 00:40:16.967
Of course, for many people here
in Connecticut, the main

00:40:16.967 --> 00:40:19.267
impact of Hurricane Irene
was losing their

00:40:19.267 --> 00:40:21.800
electrical power for days.

00:40:21.800 --> 00:40:26.633
And that's mostly in this part
of the world, because the wind

00:40:26.633 --> 00:40:30.300
will take down a tree limb and
wipe out most-- in this

00:40:30.300 --> 00:40:34.533
country, most of our power
lines are above ground.

00:40:34.533 --> 00:40:38.800
It's cheaper to do that, easy to
maintain in most cases, but

00:40:38.800 --> 00:40:41.867
they're so vulnerable
to tipping trees.

00:40:41.867 --> 00:40:44.367
So when you got a high wind
event like this, trees come

00:40:44.367 --> 00:40:46.933
down, hit the wires.

00:40:46.933 --> 00:40:49.333
You lose both communication
and power.

00:40:49.333 --> 00:40:55.500
In other parts of the world,
hurricanes are often followed

00:40:55.500 --> 00:41:00.667
a few weeks later by enormous
loss of life from disease.

00:41:00.667 --> 00:41:03.700
For example, if you have a
hurricane hitting Bangladesh

00:41:03.700 --> 00:41:07.967
or some of the other undeveloped
countries, what

00:41:07.967 --> 00:41:09.167
you'll have--

00:41:09.167 --> 00:41:11.400
the hurricane will be finished
and it'll be

00:41:11.400 --> 00:41:13.400
long gone, and then--

00:41:13.400 --> 00:41:15.800
but people will be displaced
from their homes.

00:41:15.800 --> 00:41:18.667
And more importantly, water
sources get mixed.

00:41:18.667 --> 00:41:22.567
So sewage gets into drinking
water typically, and then

00:41:22.567 --> 00:41:23.867
disease begins.

00:41:23.867 --> 00:41:26.200
And in the weeks and months that
follow, you could have

00:41:26.200 --> 00:41:30.567
hundreds, thousands, even tens
of thousands of deaths arising

00:41:30.567 --> 00:41:34.900
from the, quote, "hurricane,"
but it really has to do with

00:41:34.900 --> 00:41:38.033
just contamination of water
supplies and a lack of a

00:41:38.033 --> 00:41:41.300
public health service to be sure
that that sort of thing

00:41:41.300 --> 00:41:42.067
doesn't happen.

00:41:42.067 --> 00:41:46.500
So this is the biggest loss of
life from hurricanes by far,

00:41:46.500 --> 00:41:51.300
but these other things are
important as well.

00:41:51.300 --> 00:41:54.500
Any questions on that?

00:41:54.500 --> 00:41:59.667
So the most famous hurricane in
New England was nicknamed

00:41:59.667 --> 00:42:03.067
the Long Island Express
in 1938.

00:42:03.067 --> 00:42:08.567
It had a track like this and
hit Connecticut directly.

00:42:08.567 --> 00:42:11.067
A lot of damage along the
Connecticut coast, even more

00:42:11.067 --> 00:42:15.533
along the Rhode Island coast.
The hurricane produces its

00:42:15.533 --> 00:42:18.367
biggest damage on the right
front quadrant.

00:42:18.367 --> 00:42:21.800
So it's got four quadrants
based on how it's moving.

00:42:21.800 --> 00:42:25.800
It's that right front quadrant
that tends to have the

00:42:25.800 --> 00:42:27.800
strongest winds and in many
cases the heaviest

00:42:27.800 --> 00:42:28.900
precipitation.

00:42:28.900 --> 00:42:32.300
And in this case, that hit Rhode
Island and caused a lot

00:42:32.300 --> 00:42:33.533
of damage there.

00:42:33.533 --> 00:42:37.467
If you Google "hurricane, 1938,"
that one will pop up,

00:42:37.467 --> 00:42:39.167
and you can read all about it.

00:42:39.167 --> 00:42:41.667
It really was a major event
and is still talked about

00:42:41.667 --> 00:42:43.067
today in Connecticut.

00:42:43.067 --> 00:42:45.333
We had our own chance at this
just a few weeks ago.

00:42:45.333 --> 00:42:49.433
Hurricane Irene had a track
similar to that but not

00:42:49.433 --> 00:42:50.667
exactly the same.

00:42:50.667 --> 00:42:54.067
The difference probably was that
it brushed ashore here

00:42:54.067 --> 00:42:59.300
near Cape Hatteras and lost a
lot of its strength before it

00:42:59.300 --> 00:43:03.700
hit New England, partly by its
lack of water vapor over the

00:43:03.700 --> 00:43:05.833
land and also the frictional--

00:43:05.833 --> 00:43:09.367
with all the trees and so on
over land, that friction

00:43:09.367 --> 00:43:09.967
weakened it.

00:43:09.967 --> 00:43:14.800
So by the time it hit us, it had
weakened to a Category 2

00:43:14.800 --> 00:43:17.333
or perhaps even 1.

00:43:17.333 --> 00:43:22.267
And it still caused a lot of
flooding damage but not so

00:43:22.267 --> 00:43:26.333
much wind damage and
other things.

00:43:26.333 --> 00:43:29.133
And then of course, the most
damaging hurricane in our

00:43:29.133 --> 00:43:32.267
country's history was
Hurricane Katrina

00:43:32.267 --> 00:43:34.633
in August of 2005.

00:43:34.633 --> 00:43:35.800
And it had a different track.

00:43:35.800 --> 00:43:37.800
It started here in
the eastern--

00:43:37.800 --> 00:43:41.500
well, just north of Cuba,
crossed over the southern tip

00:43:41.500 --> 00:43:45.200
of Florida, regained
its strength, and

00:43:45.200 --> 00:43:48.600
then hit New Orleans.

00:43:48.600 --> 00:43:52.600
And you can read all about
that in the history books

00:43:52.600 --> 00:43:53.033
now-- in history
books now too.

00:43:53.033 --> 00:43:56.467
And there's a picture of Katrina
just as it was about

00:43:56.467 --> 00:44:01.500
to hit New Orleans, a
beautifully formed storm with

00:44:01.500 --> 00:44:05.800
a beautiful central eye
and the cloud shield

00:44:05.800 --> 00:44:07.633
and the whole business.

00:44:07.633 --> 00:44:15.733
Very strong storm that
hit New Orleans.

00:44:15.733 --> 00:44:17.733
This is what I mentioned
before.

00:44:17.733 --> 00:44:21.033
There's a well-defined
hurricane season.

00:44:21.033 --> 00:44:25.800
And here it is for Atlantic
hurricanes.

00:44:25.800 --> 00:44:28.200
And of course, when I say
"Atlantic," I'm referring to

00:44:28.200 --> 00:44:29.000
North Atlantic.

00:44:29.000 --> 00:44:30.800
Because, remember, there are
no hurricanes in the South

00:44:30.800 --> 00:44:34.733
Atlantic, so this is the
Northern Hemisphere hurricane

00:44:34.733 --> 00:44:36.867
frequencies for the
Atlantic Ocean.

00:44:36.867 --> 00:44:41.133
And typically, the frequency
is non-negligible even in

00:44:41.133 --> 00:44:44.467
June, but it begins to rise
quickly at the first of

00:44:44.467 --> 00:44:48.867
August, peaks in early,
mid-September, and then you're

00:44:48.867 --> 00:44:52.600
kind of out of the woods by
the time you get to the

00:44:52.600 --> 00:44:55.067
beginning or the middle
of November.

00:44:55.067 --> 00:45:01.100
And this all has to do with
ocean surface temperatures.

00:45:01.100 --> 00:45:02.367
Questions on that?

00:45:08.567 --> 00:45:09.133
Yes.

00:45:09.133 --> 00:45:13.533
Well, it is-- we have five
minutes to go, but rather than

00:45:13.533 --> 00:45:16.933
starting a new subject, why
don't we call it quits today?

00:45:16.933 --> 00:45:21.733
And we'll do mid-latitude
